    {
      "id": "17709aa662b9458bf9471209a9b6e018b4cc9cb9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 278,
        "name": "Nathaniel Clark",
        "email": "nclark@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "utopiabound"
      },
      "date": "2016-12-08 19:34:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAren't those supposed to increment and decrement the link count\n   only? Or am I wrong on that?\n\nosd_object_ref_add() and osd_object_ref_del() basically do what your patch does.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "804c9649c66a61d0c21962c988cce55c3b575f2a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 458,
        "name": "Olaf Faaland",
        "email": "faaland1@llnl.gov",
        "username": "ofaaland"
      },
      "date": "2016-12-21 01:14:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nNathaniel and Alex:\n\nThanks for looking at this.\n\nosd_object_ref_add/delete update the link count, via sa_update...SA_ZPL_LINKS().  They do not update the size, that would be sa_update...SA_ZPL_SIZE().\n\nLustre updates the size of non-ZAP objects via SA_ZPL_SIZE.  It does not appear to update the size of ZAP objects.\n\nThis came up because we have encountered issues testing DNE phase 2 where one or more llogs in update_log_dir are corrupted.  Mounting the dataset via ZPL, one cannot rmdir update_log_dir, even if it is empty, because the size is set incorrectly and ZPL checks the size as part of the rmdir code.\n\nSo the issue here is not about link count, but rather about size.\n\nThis patch may well be the wrong approach.  Suggestions are welcome.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "8cd90ee07175da11a7d8532a683fd6c6a50c0e7d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2016-12-21 04:41:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nanother unfortunate thing is that updating attributes in ZFS is _very_ expensive. on multicore systems it can be much more expensive than zap_add() and zap_remove() even .. I think we should talk to ZFS people.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d4b69e56de3751d104f6901513df778e5de79eb8",
      "author": {
